# Starr ClaimSight — Deployment Package

A self-contained static web app: one HTML file, no backend, no build step.
Deploy to Vercel in ~2 minutes.

## What's in this folder
- `index.html` .............. the entire app (double-click to preview locally too)
- `vercel.json` ............. optional static-site config (safe to keep)
- `sample-data/` ............ 33 demo claims (CSV + JSON) to upload inside the app
- `README.md` ............... this file

## Deploy to Vercel

### Option 1 — Vercel CLI (fastest)
1. Install Node.js from https://nodejs.org (if you don't have it).
2. In a terminal:  `npm i -g vercel`
3. `cd` into this folder, then run:  `vercel`
   - Log in when prompted and accept the defaults:
     Framework preset = Other, Build command = none, Output directory = ./
4. Vercel prints a preview URL. For the shareable production URL:  `vercel --prod`

### Option 2 — GitHub + Vercel (no command line)
1. Create a new repository on https://github.com and upload the contents of this folder.
2. Go to https://vercel.com  ->  Add New  ->  Project  ->  Import your repo.
3. Framework preset = Other. Leave Build & Output settings empty. Click Deploy.
4. You get a https://<name>.vercel.app URL.

### Settings that matter (don't overthink these)
- No build command, no framework, no environment variables.
- Root / output directory = the folder root, where index.html lives.

## Using it in the demo
Open the URL  ->  Catastrophic Claims  ->  "Load demo dataset" (instant),
or drag `sample-data/claims_synthetic.csv` onto the upload box.
NOTE: file upload works on the deployed URL. It does NOT work inside in-app previews.

## Next step (when ready)
Swap the in-browser classifier for a call to your cloud claims API —
that's a single-function change inside index.html. 
